{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476901"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13989"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583819"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:30:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:30:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13989"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13989"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.07,0.73,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6623"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13989"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35142"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1929"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13446"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent for a routine health check. The child was adopted at birth, and there is limited information about his birth mother\u0027s pregnancy. His parent reports concerns about the child\u0027s behaviour and learning difficulties. On examination, the child appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The examining doctor notes some distinctive facial features and is concerned about a diagnosis of Foetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of facial features is mostly likely present in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High arched palate, long philtrum, and upslanting palpebral fissures","Hypertelorism, broad nasal bridge, and micrognathia","Smooth philtrum, thin upper lip, and short palpebral fissures","Prominent forehead, wide-set eyes, and cleft lip","Low-set ears, epicanthal folds, and macroglossia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe classic facial features of Foetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder (FASD) include a \u003Cstrong\u003Esmooth philtrum, thin upper lip, and short palpebral fissures\u003C/strong\u003E. These physical features, when present together with confirmed prenatal alcohol exposure and neurodevelopmental impairments, are key diagnostic criteria for FASD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertelorism, broad nasal bridge, and micrognathia\u003C/strong\u003E are not specifically associated with FASD. These features can be seen in various other genetic syndromes, such as DiGeorge syndrome or Noonan syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-set ears, epicanthal folds, and macroglossia\u003C/strong\u003E are features more commonly associated with Down syndrome rather than FASD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProminent forehead, wide-set eyes, and cleft lip\u003C/strong\u003E are not characteristic of FASD. Cleft lip is a separate congenital anomaly that can occur independently or as part of various syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh arched palate, long philtrum, and upslanting palpebral fissures\u003C/strong\u003E are features that can be seen in some genetic conditions like Marfan syndrome, but are not typical of FASD. In fact, FASD is characterised by a short philtrum, not a long one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to appreciated that while these facial features are characteristic of FASD, a formal diagnosis requires a comprehensive assessment and this includes confirmation of prenatal alcohol exposure and evaluation of multiple domains of functioning, such as cognition, self-regulation, and adaptive behaviour. The facial features alone are not sufficient for diagnosis. Early identification and intervention can significantly improve outcomes for children with FASD, highlighting the importance of recognising these features in clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The classic facial features of Foetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder (FASD) include smooth philtrum, thin upper lip, and short palpebral fissures.","Diagnosis of FASD requires confirmation of prenatal alcohol exposure and assessment of multiple domains of functioning.","Early diagnosis and intervention can significantly improve outcomes for children with FASD."],"references":["Chudley AE, Cook JL, Loock C. Fetal alcohol spectrum disorder: Clinical features and diagnosis. UpToDate. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/fetal-alcohol-spectrum-disorder-clinical-features-and-diagnosis?search=fasd\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1%7E39\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35142"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13989"}},"s